@Node "Intro" "Introduction"
@Prev "Main"
@Next "Usage"

@{bd "Introduction"}

When @{"LhA" link LhA} came along, Amiga users were able to store files in one (generally)
smaller  file - an @{b}LhA@{ub} @{"archive" link Arc} . Then @{"LZX" link LZX} came along - allowing much better
compression  rates  for  some  files,  so  much  more  space could be saved.
	When I first got  @{b}LZX@{ub}  I found it a lot of work converting  my old  @{b}LhA@{ub}
archives  to  the new @{b}LZX@{ub} format via the @{"CLI" link CLI}, and sometimes found that after
doing it that my original @{b}LhA@{ub} files were smaller than the new @{b}LZX@{ub} ones! Thus
@{bl "LhA2LZX"} was born. This script file allows the user to convert their archives
from  @{b}LhA@{ub}  to  @{b}LZX@{ub}  or  vice  versa,  or alternatively it will intelligently
convert  the  archive  to  the smallest format! It is all done by requesters
 - so you don't even need to touch the keyboard!

And new for  @{"v3.0" link Hist3 4}  is the ability to easily  use it @{b}directly@{ub} from @{bl "Directory
Opus"},  and also to @{b}repack@{ub}  each  archive to  make sure the @{b}maximum@{ub} amount of
space  is saved!  Just @{b}select@{ub}  the files  you wish  to  convert, and @{b}click@{ub} a
button!

This program is an  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}  @{"script" LINK "scripts"} file,  so  you can  load it into a text
viewer/editor and  see how it all works.  Almost  all of the lines have been
commented to help you understand this.

@{bl "LhA2LZX"} also supports @{b}LZH@{ub} archives (they are very similar to LhA).


@{bd "In a nutshell..."}

@{bl "LhA2LZX"} can perform several different actions:

- It can convert archives @{b}between@{ub} the two formats
	(e.g. give it an  LhA archive  and it  will @{b}convert@{ub} it to  LZX, or vice
	versa)
- It can convert to the @{b}smaller@{ub} of the two archives
	(e.g. give  it an  LhA  archive  and it  will @{b}create@{ub}  the  LZX version,
	@{b}compare@{ub} the  size with the  LhA version and @{b}save@{ub} the  smallest, or vice
	versa)
- It can @{b}repack@{ub} an archive
	(e.g. give it an LhA archive  and it will  @{b}de-archive@{ub} it and @{b}re-archive@{ub}
	it with @{b}LhA@{ub} to  make sure it is the  @{b}smallest@{ub} size for  that particular
	format)


@Endnode

@Node "Usage" "How to use LhA2LZX"
@Prev "Intro"
@Next "Reqs"

@{bd "How To Use"}

- To begin with,you can @{b}install@{ub} @{bl "LhA2LZX"} using the @{b}installer@{ub} script provided.
	A @{b}full@{ub}  install  will install  @{b}everything@{ub}  in the archive,  and a @{b}basic@{ub}
	install  will just install  the @{b}latest@{ub}  version of  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  with  this
	.@{b}guide@{ub}.  You will need the @{b}full@{ub} install to access @{b}all@{ub} functions in this
	document.  Remember that one function of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} as an on-going process
	is to help  teach how  to write  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} scripts, and so  some of  the
	previous versions are accessed from this .@{b}guide@{ub}.
- Don't forget to copy '@{b}inf@{ub}' from the @{b}util/cli/mykinf.lha@{ub} archive to @{b}C:@{ub} , or
	at least to somewhere in your path
- To run from @{bl "Workbench"}, @{b}Double-click@{ub} on the @{"LhA2LZX" SYSTEM "run LhA2LZX"} icon
- To run from the @{bl "CLI"}, @{b}cd@{ub} to the drawer @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is in and type

		@{fg shine}LhA2LZX@{fg text}

	You may also follow this with an archive name:

		@{fg shine}LhA2LZX "dh1:Temp/new.lzx"@{fg text}

	If you do not @{b}CD@{ub} to the drawer, you will get an  error message  telling
	you to  do so.  You  may omit  the quotes  unless the  archive path has
	spaces in.
- To run from @{bl "Directory Opus"}, follow the specific instructions below.

- The first time you use  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, you will be prompted for a path where the
	temporary drawer  '@{b}l2z@{ub}'  is to be created - this  is used to de-archive
	the files in the archive during the operation. There should be at least
	@{b}3-4@{ub} times the size of the original archive here. The path is then saved
	to a file '@{b}LhA2LZXl2zpath@{ub}' in @{b}ENVARC@{ub}:,and will be used in all following
	sessions.  Sometimes you may not have  enough memory to use @{b}RAM@{ub}: as the
	default path (which is recommended as it  is much faster), and you will
	be prompted to choose another path. This @{b}new@{ub} path will then replace the
	old.  If  you  wish  to ever  change  the path,  just  delete  the file
	'@{b}env:LhA2LZXl2zpath@{ub}' and run @{bl "LhA2LZX"} again
- @{b}Select@{ub} the @{b}archive(s)@{ub} from the file requester
- Choose  whether to convert  to the @{b}other@{ub}  archive type (i.e. @{b}LhA to LZX@{ub} or
	@{b}LZX to LhA@{ub}), to the @{b}smallest@{ub} archive or to @{b}repack@{ub} the archive.


@{bd "Using"} @{bl "@{U}LhA2LZX@{UU}"} @{bd "in"} @{bl "@{U}DOpus@{UU}"}

As of @{"v3.0" link Hist3 4},@{bl "LhA2LZX"} has now been modified for use as a @{bl "Directory Opus"} button.
I use  @{b}v5.11@{ub}, but it  should work on  any @{b}v5.0+@{ub}.  Please let me  know if  it
doesn't.

- Create a new button, and set up the function as follows:

@{fg shine}AmigaDOS	cd "@{fg fill}LhA2LZXdrawer@{fg shine}"
AmigaDOS	list {F} >RAM:LhA2LZX.exe LFORMAT="execute *"@{fg fill}LhA2LZXdrawer@{fg shine}/LhA2LZX*" *"%F%N*""
AmigaDOS	execute ram:lha2lzx.exe
AmigaDOS	delete ram:lha2lzx.exe@{fg text}

where @{fg fill}LhA2LZXdrawer@{fg text} is the path of the @{bl "LhA2LZX"} program drawer e.g. @{b}dh1:temp@{ub}

- Set the flags "@{b}CD source@{ub}" and "@{b}Rescan source@{ub}".
- To use, @{b}select@{ub} the archive(s) and click the button.
- Each archive will be processed @{b}in turn@{ub}
- You will  know when  each  process has finished  because the source @{b}lister@{ub}
	will be  @{b}rescanned@{ub},  and you will get  the @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  messages  detailing
	which archive is being used.  Do not worry if the @{b}lister@{ub} stays busy for
	a moment - it is  just @{bl "LhA2LZX"} cleaning  up after itself or  processing
	the archive.


@{bd "Notes"}

@{bl "LhA2LZX"}  can be stopped during execution by  pressing @{b}Control-D@{ub} or @{b}Control-C@{ub}

If you know that you aren't going to change the location of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, you can
copy the file  @{fg shine}ENV:LhA2LZXpath@{fg text} to @{fg shine}ENVARC:@{fg text} to save  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  working out it's
own location each time it is run.  You will  need to delete @{i}both @{ui}these files
if you decide to move @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, but then you can copy the new @{fg shine}ENV:LhA2LZXpath@{fg text}
over to @{fg shine}ENVARC:@{fg text} after running @{bl "LhA2LZX"} from the new drawer.  

If you want to  see exactly  how @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  works,  get @{b}KingCON@{ub}  (an excellent
Shell replacement which gives a scrollbar on the side of the CLI window) and
type @{fg shine}set echo on@{fg text} before  running  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  from there.  This will give you a
line-by-line  output  of what  is happening,  and is  very easy  to read and
compare with the original @{bl "LhA2LZX"} code to see how, amongst other things, the
@{"Environment Variables" link Env} work,  and  how  all the  bits  fit together.  This is
available on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub} as @{b}util/shell/KingCON_1.3.lha@{ub}.  If you  want to send
a really good bug  report,  simply cut-&-paste the output  from  the @{b}KingCON@{ub}
window into an e-mail or attachment so I  can see exactly where and what the
problem is :^)

If the screen keeps flipping between  @{bl "Workbench"}  and  @{bl "DOpus"}  when requesters
appear  (if @{bl "DOpus"}  isn't  the  default  public screen),  try using @{b}ARQ@{ub},  the
requester improver, available on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub} as @{b}util/cdity/Arq1_83.lha@{ub}.  This
has the added bonus of  adding small  animations in  the requester,  and the
possibility to add sounds to specific requester types.

I'd also recommend using a colour of 32,70,222 for the  fourth (@{bl "blue"}) colour
in your palette for reading this .guide, and a proportional font.

From @{"v3.1" link Hist3 198},@{bl "LhA2LZX"} will invoke an @{"AREXX" LINK "AREXX"} script to handle various things that
AmigaDOS cannot,so you should have the program @{b}Sys:System/RexxMast@{ub}, and also
the following commands somewhere in your startup:

@{fg shine}ASSIGN REXX: S:
PATH Sys:system sys:rexxc ADD
RexxMast >nil:@{fg text}

The  last one  is optional, it just starts  @{b}RexxMast@{ub}  so that  it is already
resident.  The  first  two command  lines above  should  already be  in your
startup-sequence.  The installer script will automatically copy @{"lha2lzx.rexx" link REXX:lha2lzx.rexx/MAIN}
over to  wherever @{b}REXX@{ub}:  is assigned to,  as this is where  the command that
starts @{"AREXX" LINK "AREXX"} scripts, @{b}RX@{ub}, looks for them.
@Endnode

@Node "Reqs" "Requirements - What you need to run LhA2LZX"
@Prev "Usage"
@Next "Scripts"

@{bd "Requirements"}

@{bl "LhA2LZX"} requires several things to work:
@{i}[	BaseName				(1.3, arp component)		] @{ui}
	CD					(2.x/3.x internal)
	Copy					(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Delete				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Echo					(2.x/3.x internal)
	Else					(2.x/3.x internal)
	Endif				(2.x/3.x internal)
	Eval					(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Filenote				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Inf					util/cli/mykinf.lha on AmiNET, put in C:
	If					(2.x/3.x internal)
	Lab					(2.x/3.x in C:)
	List					(2.x/3.x in C:)
	MakeDir				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Protect				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Quit					(2.x/3.x internal)
	Rename				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	RequestChoice 			(3.x only, located in C:)
	RequestFile 			(3.x only, located in C:)
	Resident				(2.x/3.x internal)
	RX					(2.x/3.x in Sys:REXXC)
	Search				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	SetDate				(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Skip					(2.x/3.x internal)
	Type					(2.x/3.x in C:)
	Which				(2.x/3.x in C:)

As indicated, you will already have these either in @{b}ROM@{ub} or on your @{b}Workbench@{ub}
disks in the @{b}C@{ub}: drawer (or already on your hard disk).

A @{b}hard disk@{ub} is greatly recommended,and some spare @{b}RAM@{ub} (depending on the size
of the archives you are converting).

Both the @{"LhA" link LhA} and @{"LZX" link LZX} tools will also be needed - preferably in @{b}C:@{ub}
 @{i}[these are both available on the AmiNET, and from most PD libraries] @{ui}

@{b}LhA@{ub} can be found at @{b}util/arc/LhA_e138.run@{ub} and @{b}LZX@{ub} is at @{b}util/arc/lzx121r1.lha@{ub}
on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub}.

Since @{"v2.6" link Hist2 136} the @{b}registered@{ub} version of @{b}LZX@{ub} is needed - and the @{B}registered
keyfile@{UB} is now freely available and part of the @{b}LZX@{ub} distribution.

@{b}IconX@{ub} will also be needed in @{b}C:@{ub} if you want to double-click the icon to
start @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

From @{"v2.3" link Hist2 95}+ of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, @{b}BaseName@{ub} is no longer used.

From @{"v2.7a" link Hist2 170}+, a 68020 or faster CPU is needed.

Versions of @{"RequestChoice" link ReqC} & @{"RequestFile" link ReqF} for @{b}2.x@{ub} are available on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub}.

@{b}Tested on:@{ub}

A1200, 25Mhz '020 + FPU (Apollo Turbo 1220), 170 MB HD, 2/4 MB RAM, KS 3.1
A1200, 25Mhz '030 + FPU (Blizzard), 580 MB HD, 2/4 MB RAM, KS 3.1
A1200, 40Mhz '030 + FPU (Apollo 1230), 2.1 GB HD, 2/14 MB RAM, KS 3.1

@{b}Untested@{ub} on @{b}KS 2.x@{ub}.
If you can test it on any of these, please mail me with the results :^)

@Endnode

@Node "Scripts" "Writing AmigaDOS Scripts"
@Prev "Reqs"
@Next "Bugs"

@{bd "Writing AmigaDos Scripts"}							@{" Read LhA2LZX " Link LhA2LZX/Main}

@{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}  scripts are very useful because everyone who has @{b}Workbench@{ub} has the
necessary  software  to write  and run them.  They are written in a language
which is easy to  learn  and easy to  understand, and can be used to do many
things. The @{b}startup-sequence@{ub}  is the most well  known of these  scripts, and
shows just what they can do.Programs can be called and started,and @{"arguments" link Args}
can be passed to them, which is essentially how @{bl "LhA2LZX"} works - @{"LhA" link LhA} and @{"LZX" link LZX}
are  called from  the @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  script and the  arguments that  the user  has
selected are passed to them.  An important aspect  of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is the use  of
@{"Environment Variables" link Env}.

Scripts  are written using a text editor (such as @{b}Ed@{ub}), and do not need to be
compiled,  so  you  can  simply run them from @{b}Workbench@{ub} or the @{"CLI" link CLI} (which is
great  when  you're writing  them - just the click of a button to test it!).

Comments  (anything  written  after  a  semi-colon "@{b};@{ub}") are ignored when the
script  is  running,  so don't be afraid to comment your file so you clearly
know  what  bit  does  what. They will not affect the actions of the script.

If  you  do not have an @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} manual,  detailing what all the keywords do
(there  wasn't  one  in the @{b}A1200@{ub} distribution), there are many available in
the @{b}Public Domain@{ub} - the one I use is the  fantastic @{"DOSMan" link WhatUse 20} by @{b}Peter Bagnato@{ub}
which  details  the  usage  of  commands  up to and including the new @{b}WB 3.1@{ub}
ones,  and  gives  examples of how to use them. Also get your hands on other
script  files such  as the  other ones I have done @{" " link Also}, or @{"DiskSqueeze" link WhatUse 12}, a @{b}DMS@{ub}
alternative that crunches entire disks with @{b}LZX@{ub}! That file helped greatly in
creating @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

The best way to learn  script writing  techniques is  to read loads of other
scripts, making  sure you understand them,  and experimenting if  you do not
(and even if you do!).   Trying things out for yourself is a Good Thing(TM).
If you read @{bl "LhA2LZX"} and everything in the @{"Program History" link "Hist"} page, you can't go
far wrong :^)
@Endnode

@Node "Args" "Arguments"
@Prev "Scripts"
@Next "Env"

@{bd "Arguments"}

Arguments are the keywords  that follow  the program's name  if started from
the @{"CLI" link CLI},and tell the program (for example) which file(s) to use, any special
command or options to use and so on.

For example, if you typed

	@{fg shine}LZX ?@{fg text}

in a CLI, you would get a list of the arguments you can use:

	@{fg fill}LZX [-<options>] <command> <archive> [<file>...] [<destdir>]@{fg text}

where @{b}options@{ub} are any options (such as make filenames uppercase)
      @{b}command@{ub} is what action you are performing (e.g. archiving)
      @{b}archive@{ub} is the name of the archive e.g. to be saved
      @{b}file@{ub} is the name(s) of the file(s) to be e.g. archived
      @{b}destdir@{ub} is the name of the destination drawer where the archive  is
                                                           e.g. to be saved.

@{fg shine}e.g.@{fg text}
	if you typed at a CLI

		@{fg shine}LZX -F a Test.lzx dh0:Games/#? dh1:@{fg text}

	you would be archiving all (@{b}#?@{ub}) the files in the @{fg shine}dh0:Games/@{fg text} drawer,
	with a @{b}F@{ub}ast  progress display  (-F) and the  archive would  be saved as
	@{b}Test.lzx@{ub} in the @{fg shine}dh1:@{fg text} drawer.

@Endnode

@Node "Env" "Environment Variables"
@Prev "Args"
@Next "Bugs"

@{bd "Environment Variables"}

Environment  Variables  are exceedingly useful in script files as they allow
numbers  or  text  to be saved to a small file in @{b}ENV:@{ub} (in @{b}RAM:@{ub}) and used by
any program. What makes them so useful is that if a dollar sign ($) preceeds
the  filename  when it is called, the contents of the file are used instead.
So  if  for  instance the text @{fg shine}dh0:Games/@{fg text} was saved as the file @{b}ENV:zxc@{ub}, and
you typed

	@{fg shine}cd $zxc@{fg text}

in a CLI, the current drawer  would change to @{b}dh0:Games/@{ub} - just as if you
had typed

	@{fg shine}cd dh0:Games/@{fg text}

Here is a relevant part of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} that shows this:
@{JRIGHT}@{"Click to find in LhA2LZX" LINK "LhA2LZX_v2.3/MAIN" 153}
@{JLEFT}@{fg shine}if $suf EQ lha@{fg text}
	@{fg shine}cd $drw1
	cd l2z
	$wlha x -a -F -M -x $ldfl@{fg text}

Previously in the script, @{b}List@{ub} was used (found in @{b}C:@{ub}) to get the suffix (all
the  letters  after  the final full stop in the filename) of the filename to
determine  if  it was an @{b}LhA@{ub} or @{b}LZX@{ub} archive, and the suffix was saved as the
file  @{b}ENV:suf@{ub}.  So if the file is an @{b}LhA@{ub} archive, the line would be the same
as  "@{fg shine}if  lha  EQUALS  lha@{fg text}".  It  would then  @{b}cd@{ub} to the  drawer  the user had
chosen to  put the temporary  storage  drawer @{b}l2z@{ub},  and would  then @{b}cd@{ub}  into
@{b}l2z@{ub} itself.Next it would call @{b}LhA@{ub}(with the location of the @{b}LhA@{ub} program saved
as the file @{b}ENV:wlha@{ub}) and e@{b}x@{ub}tract all the files, preserving their @{b}a@{ub}ttributes
(-a)  from  the  chosen  archive  (the  filename  of the archive is saved as
@{b}ENV:ldfl@{ub}), with a  @{b}F@{ub}ast progress display (-F), preserving the path names(-x)
with  no  "autoshow"  files (which automatically display themselves when @{b}LhA@{ub}
de-/archives  them). So if  @{b}LhA@{ub}  was  in  @{b}C:@{ub}  and  the  archive  was  called
@{fg shine}dh1:Test.lha@{fg text}(which would have been selected by the user via a requester),the
final line would be the same as

	@{fg shine}C:LhA x -a -F -M -x dh1:Test.lha@{fg text}

Environment Variables can be used also to store numbers:
@{JRIGHT}@{"Click to find in LhA2LZX" LINK "LhA2LZX_v2.2/MAIN" 86}
@{JLEFT}	@{fg shine}eval >env:flmem $flsz * 4@{fg text}
@{JRIGHT}@{"More info" link Hist 107}
@{JLEFT}This  line  calls  @{b}Eval@{ub}  (in  @{b}C:@{ub}),  and tells it to multiply the size of the
original  archive  (found with @{b}List@{ub} and saved as @{b}ENV:flsz@{ub}) by 4, and to save
the  answer  as  @{b}ENV:flmem@{ub} instead of printing it to screen. This is used in
@{bl "LhA2LZX"}  to determine if the user's machine has enough memory to perform the
action  of de-/archiving (@{b}LZX@{ub} archives can de-archive sometimes to 3-4 times
the  size  of the archive) if they have chosen @{b}RAM:@{ub} to temporarily store the
files  of  the archive, and warns them if there may be insufficient memory -
note  here  that file redirection is used (the @{b}>@{ub} sign), which enables user's
choices to be saved in files rather than be printed to the screen.

@{b}When  creating  your own script files, it is a sound idea for the very first
line to be

	@{fg shine}set echo on@{fg text}

as  this  will give a display of all the actions being performed, so you can
see exactly what is happening and where things need to be changed to fix any
problems.  This  can  be  deleted when the script is finished and everything
works  as  you  would  want  it  to.@{ub}

@Endnode

@node "Lisa" "Lisa Loeb - Cutest Rock Chick Queen in The World!"

It's hidden page number 3!

No explanation needed here about the wonderful @{bg highlight}Lisa Loeb@{bg background}!  Just go buy one
of her albums - @{b}Tails@{ub} or @{b}Firecracker@{ub} - and prepare to be transfixed forever!
Her albums are @{I}so good @{UI}that you can leave them in your CD player for @{I}months @{UI}
without tiring of them!  So go on then.  Treat yourself.  In fact, I'm just
off to go put @{b}Firecracker@{ub} on...again...

@{I}[muffled sounds of inept teenager fiddling with a beautifully pink CD 
case...] @{UI}


@{b}Clue Four:	How best would I describe my beautiful girlfriend?  In a word
			of 9 letters?  That's on this page?@{ub}
@endnode

@Node "Bugs" "Bugs in LhA2LZX"
@Prev "Scripts"
@Next "Hist"

@{bd "Problems"}

Apparently the @{b}clear screen@{ub} command (@{b}echo@{ub} "@{fg shine}*ec@{fg text}") doesn't work for @{b}KS 2.0@{ub}, so
I changed it back to "@{fg shine}*e[1;1H*eJ@{fg text}" in @{"v2.6a" link Hist2 144} (this moves the cursor to  @{b}column
1 row 1@{ub} and @{b}clears@{ub} all that follows it).

When  @{b}de-archiving@{ub},  if it encounters an empty drawer,  @{b}LZX@{ub} may  display the
error message

	@{fg shine}*** LZX: Error writing to disk; disk full?@{fg text}

but still continues to @{b}de-archive@{ub} regardless. This seems to be a bug in @{b}LZX@{ub},
and seems to have  no effect on the process.  When the files are @{b}archived@{ub} by
@{b}LhA@{ub}  seconds  later,  the  empty  directories  are  also @{b}archived@{ub} as normal.

@{b}e.g.@{ub}	Here is a copy of the output from one of my tests:
@{LINDENT 1}
@{fg fill}LZX 1.21 (Registered) Archive/Extract utility - 68020/68030 Version.
Copyright © 1995 Data Compression Technologies.  All rights reserved.
Registered to the Amiga community for non-commercial use.

Extracting files from archive 'AQ2:DiskSalv/Executive.lzx':
 (       0 /       0) executive_v2.10/empty/ (       0 /       0) executive
*** LZX: Error writing to disk; disk full?
 (       0 /       0) executive_v2.10/c/empty2/empty3/ (       0 /       0)
*** LZX: Error writing to disk; disk full?
  ** 30 file(s) extracted, all files OK

Operation successful

LhA Evaluation V1.51 - Copyright (c) 1992 by Stefan Boberg.     
All rights reserved. Not for commercial use.

Creating new archive 'Executive.lha':
	Frozen: ( 52.4%)    3604 =>   1713 : executive_v2.10/.Product-Info
	Archiving empty directory `executive_v2.10/c/empty2/empty3'
	Frozen: (  6.0%)    3576 =>   3360 : executive_v2.10/data/DashboardPrefs.l
	Stored: (  0.0%)   38661 =>  38661 : executive_v2.10/data/Register.lzx
	Archiving empty directory `executive_v2.10/empty'
30 files added, all files OK.

Operation successful.@{fg text}
@{LINDENT 0}
As can  be  seen  above,  the empty directories I added ("@{fg shine}c/empty2/empty3@{fg text}" &
"@{fg shine}empty@{fg text}") are still archived,so the message does not seem to affect anything.
For clarity,the disk was @{i}not @{ui}full.


@{bd "The Tilde (~) Bug"}   (fixed in @{"v3.1" link Hist3 198})

Since having access to the @{b}AmiNET@{ub},  I have found an additional bug, and that
is @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}'s and @{b}LZX@{ub}'s inability to handle @{b}tilde's@{ub} (~) in filenames.I found
this when copying files from the PC's here at University to my disks to take
back to my trusty  Amiga,  when if a filename is greater than  8  characters
long  (suffix not included), it is  truncated:  so for  instance an  archive
called "@{fg shine}longarcname.lha@{fg text}" would be renamed "@{fg shine}longar~1.lha@{fg text}" when saved to disk.
When I tried to use these in  @{bl "LhA2LZX"},  @{b}LZX@{ub} would not do anything with them,
but gave an output of @{fg fill}Operation successful@{fg text}.  I have tried getting round this
by detecting a @{b}tilde@{ub} in  a  filename  and  getting  the  user to input a new
filename,  but @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} treats tilde's as something to do with @{b}negation@{ub} - it
is used in @{b}pattern-matching@{ub}. If you want to get a list of all the files in a
drawer, you would type
	@{fg fill}list #?@{fg text}
If you wanted a list of  all the files @{b}except@{ub} for the @{b}icon@{ub} files,  you would
type
	@{fg fill}list ~(#?.info)@{fg text}
which would list all the files apart from those ending in @{b}info@{ub} (icon files).
So it seems if an archive has a @{b}tilde@{ub} in it's name, @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} and @{b}LZX@{ub} try to
operate on it in a @{b}pattern-matching@{ub} context.

Using the @{b}Type@{ub} command was the closest I got (e.g.
	@{fg fill}Type FROM arc~2.lzx TO arc2.lzx@{fg text}
but the command only  copied part of  the file.  I tried also @{fg fill}Copy@{fg text}, @{fg fill}Join@{fg text} and
@{fg fill}Rename@{fg text}, but these didn't change the filename either.  The only way to change
the filename via the @{b}CLI@{ub} would be to use the @{b}apostrophe@{ub} (') before the tilde
e.g. if your archive was called @{fg shine}my~arc.lzx@{fg text}:
	@{fg fill}Rename my'~arc.lzx TO myarc.lzx@{fg text}

This bug was fixed  in @{"v3.1" link Hist3 198},  by use of an @{"AREXX" LINK "AREXX"} script.  I was able to get
the above command line by finding the position of any tilde's and  inserting
an apostrophe before them.

Thanks to @{"Frank Bunton" link Thanks} for the help here, both with how to rename such files
by the CLI and by writing the fabulous "AREXX For Beginners".

There was a bug found in the @{b}68000@{ub} version of @{b}LZX@{ub} (which is why you now need
to use the '@{b}020@{ub} or higher version), and this is discussed fully in the
program history for @{"v2.7a" link Hist2 170}.

Another bug which may appear has come about  in @{"v3.0" link Hist3 4}.  The size  of the file
listing of the @{b}RAM:@{ub} disk is found as a  check to see if any files have  been
selected for conversion  -  if  the file listing of your archives is @{I}exactly @{UI}
the  same  as the  entire @{b}RAM:@{ub}  listing,  @{bl "LhA2LZX"} will  think you  have  not
selected any files, although  the chances of this are remote.  To get around
it, just put your archives in a different place and convert them from there,
or copy a file over to  @{b}RAM:@{ub} (which  will then change the  listing size) and
try again.


This AmigaGuide has been tested only on WB3.1, so it is possible not all  of
the keywords will work under 3.0 or below systems.  If anyone can read  this
on  any other WB version,  please contact me  (you can load this into a text
viewer and read what all the missing words,if any, are). If all is not well,
I will change it.

@{b}Bug reports@{ub} and @{b}suggestions of improvement@{ub} are welcome.

Feel free to try out the @{i}first versions @{ui}of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} (i.e. 1.x),  but only use
copies  of  your  archives  as they have bugs in - hence you can see where I
improved it...  :^)

@Endnode

@node "wonderful" "Aw...."

I'm putting in my final secret page dedicated to my wonderful girlfriend
Leann.  Everyone else seems to thank their girlfriends in the credits, so I
thought I might as well do it too.  So...

...Leann, thanks for being so great in all the time we've known each other,
		and an extra big thanks for all the time we've been together.

@{I}"She can't tell me that all of the love songs have been written,
'cause she's never been in love with you before..."
										- Lisa Loeb, "Sandalwood" @{UI}

@endnode

@Node "Hist" "Program History & Development"
@Prev "Bugs"
@Next "Hist2"

@{bd "Program History"}

Versions @{"v3.0" link Hist3 4} - @{"v3.2a" link Hist3 282}  are included in this distribution so you can
see how it developed.  Files are commented from @{b}2.0+@{ub}.

Versions @{b}1.1@{ub}, @{b}1.2@{ub}, @{"2.0" link Hist2 4} - @{"2.8" link Hist2 250} are now available on the AmiNET as
util/arc/LhA2LZX2.lha

Version No.
~~~~~~~~~~~
@{h "1.0"}	Initial incarnation

@{h "1.1"}	Added filesize difference to show which archive was smallest

@{h "1.2"}	Fixed  bug  of  '@{b}l2z@{ub}' not  being  deleted if  the original archive  was
	smaller. The following extract is from the original docs:

	"- DO NOT QUIT WHEN DE-ARCHIVING  otherwise  ONLY  THE  FILES CURRENTLY
	DE-ARCHIVED WILL BE PLACED IN THE NEW ARCHIVE. The new archive will not
	contain all the original files and will overwrite the ORIGINAL archive.

	So DON'T DO IT!

	This happens  because it  is an @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} @{"script" link Scripts} file,  and will perform
	the next  action @{b}immediately@{ub} after completing the previous one. Thus if
	it is @{b}de-archiving@{ub}  and it is  interrupted by a @{b}CTRL-C@{ub}, it will perform
	the next  action of  @{b}archiving@{ub} everything it has (so far) @{b}de-archived@{ub}."

	I  found  that  if  I  aborted  either @{b}LhA@{ub}  or  @{b}LZX@{ub}  whilst  they  were
	@{b}de-/archiving@{ub} then some of the original files were lost and, due to the
	nature of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}'s  workings, were  @{b}irretrievable@{ub}  unless a backup was
	kept. @{bl "LhA2LZX"} was  such that after it had @{b}de-archived@{ub} and @{b}archived@{ub}, the
	new file would  replace the old, so files would be lost if this process
	was interrupted - some of the original files would not be  @{b}archived@{ub} and
	then the new would replace the old. Not a good thing. This was fixed in
	@{"v2.1" link Hist2 25}.

@EndNode

@Node "Hist2" "Program History & Development - v2.x"
@Prev "Hist"
@Next "Hist3"

@{bd "Program History - v2.x"}

@{h "2.0"}	Added the extra option to convert to the other filetype.  This was done
	for 2 main reasons.  Firstly in  case the user merely wished to convert
	between the filetypes, and secondly so I could convert my @{b}.lzx@{ub} files to
	@{b}.lha@{ub},allowing me to enter them @{b}interactively@{ub} via @{bl "DOpus5"} and add to them
	- my version of @{b}LZXDir 26.6.95 v1.1 (modified by Stone-D)@{ub} doesn't allow
	me to add to @{b}.lzx@{ub} files @{b}interactively@{ub}.

	@{bd "Note"}
	@{bl "Directory Opus"} is a @{b}filemanager@{ub} which allows  you to quickly and easily
	perform actions on files.  @{b}LhADir@{ub} & @{b}LZXDir@{ub}  are two add-ons ("@{b}modules@{ub}")
	which  allow  you to  enter an @{b}.lha@{ub}/@{b}.lzx@{ub}  file as  if it were a  normal
	@{b}drawer@{ub}  and  perform  actions  on  the  files  within,  @{b}e.g.@{ub} viewing  a
	picture, as well as @{b}deleting@{ub} and @{b}adding@{ub}  files to the @{b}archive@{ub} as if you
	were merely transferring files  from one drawer to another.  If I  want
	to add a file to  an @{b}.lzx@{ub} archive  however I  have to convert  it to an
	@{b}.lha@{ub} archive due to the version I have.If anyone has an updated version
	of @{b}LZXDir@{ub}, please feel free to send it to me.

	This  version of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} also checked  if the file was  already of  the
	type that the user wished to convert to.

@{h "2.1"}	Added routines to check if the @{b}FULL@{ub} path of the @{b}archive@{ub} was chosen from
	the file requester by checking the  size of the path name. Also did the
	same to check that a file had been chosen.Altered the "@{b}Convert to. . ?@{ub}"
	routine  to @{b}automatically@{ub} check  the filetype as this made  things more
	logical (previously you could try to convert an @{b}.lha@{ub} archive to an @{b}.lha@{ub}
	archive . . .), and also saved me from trying to remember what type I'd
	just converted  the file to.  The routine allowing the checking of  the
	filetype  was already being  used in @{bl "LhA2LZX"},  so it was  really just a
	cut-&-paste job once I'd realised it.

	@{b}* MAJOR BUG FIX *@{ub}
	Stumbled  across the  means to add @{b}error  detection@{ub} if  something  went
	wrong in the @{b}de-/archiving@{ub} process! @{b}@{i}BIG @{ub}@{ui}thanks to @{b}Peter Bagnato@{ub} and his
	@{"DOSMan" link WhatUse 20}  creation  -  an  @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub}  detailing  the usage  of  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}
	commands, with examples  -  which is a boon to those of us that haven't
	got  an  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}  reference  manual.  Fixing  this  bug meant  that if
	anything  went  wrong when  @{b}de-/archiving@{ub}  (such as a  @{b}user  abort@{ub} or a
	@{b}corrupt file@{ub}), then @{bl "LhA2LZX"} would stop immediately and so all archives,
	the new and the original, would remain intact. And all by adding only 6
	lines of code . . . I could now sleep at night.

@{h "2.2"}	I deleted all the 'deletes' at the start of the file  as I decided that
	they were unnecessary. If @{bl "LhA2LZX"} had been quitted and then re-started,
	the @{b}env:@{ub} files  would  have already been  deleted when  it was quit the
	first time. If it was being started for the first time, chances are the
	files wouldn't  be there anyway as  @{b}env:@{ub} is a temporary drawer  in @{b}RAM:@{ub}
	and therefore erased with each reset. If the user chose to convert more
	archives(the final requester of the program), then the @{b}env:@{ub} files would
	be overwritten with the new variables. This also allowed me to  use the
	@{b}drawer@{ub} of  the @{b}last  archive chosen@{ub}  as the  @{b}default path@{ub}  for the next
	archive  - something I had wanted to do from the start - as it saves on
	searching  through all of  your  directories if you have  a drawer with
	several archives in which you wish to convert.

	I also changed the new  archive copying routine to copy the new archive
	to the selected destination @{b}BEFORE@{ub} deleting the old in case of mishaps,
	but  then altered  it back for two reasons  -  there  may not be enough
	space  in the  destination, especially  if  it is a floppy,  to contain
	both the archives  (new & old) before  the old is  deleted, and also it
	would now make little difference as this part of the script would never
	be reached  if something  @{b}DID@{ub}  go wrong  when it was @{b}de-/archiving@{ub}, now
	that the @{b}error detection@{ub} was in place.

	The "@{b}Convert to . . ?@{ub}" requester was  changed  to show the  filename in
	the title bar. The output messages detailing  which archive is  smaller
	were put into requesters to lessen the output in the CLI window - but I
	had to sacrifice the @{b}ANSI@{ub} colouring to do this. Now the only @{b}CLI@{ub} output
	to screen  is the coloured  closing message,  which is displayed whilst
	all the temporary files created are deleted.

	@{b}Amount of free memory is checked@{ub}  if the '@{b}l2z@{ub}' is selected in @{b}RAM:@{ub},  to
	make sure you won't run out,  and a  requester pops  up advising you if
	this might happen. I would also like to  find the amount  of free space
	of  the  destination  drawer (in  case  @{b}RAM:@{ub} isn't  chosen) to  see  if
	there is  enough, but  I haven't yet  found a way  to do this using the
	@{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} files in the @{b}Workbench@{ub} distribution.

	A clever trick is also employed here  -  that of using  the @{b}backtick@{ub} `.
	You can  surround  a command by these  and pass this as an argument  to
	another command.  The command in the  backticks is evaluated first, and
	the result is then passed to the first command

	e.g.
	@{fg shine}echo `eval 2+2`@{fg text}

	would  call @{b}Eval@{ub}  (which performs numerical  functions), pass @{b}2+2@{ub} to it
	(which  would give the answer @{b}4@{ub}), and pass the anwser @{b}4@{ub} to @{b}Echo@{ub},  which
	would then print  the answer to  the screen.  It would be  exactly like
	typing @{fg shine}echo 4@{fg text}, and that is how @{fg shine}echo@{fg text} would see it.

@{h "2.3"}	@{b}BaseName@{ub} now is no  longer used, as a function of @{b}List@{ub} is used instead,
	to give the filename without a suffix and the suffix on its own.Deleted
	a couple of deletions of environment variables as they were overwritten
	on the following line, and so  were unnecessary.  Added a small routine
	just to check that the archive name @{i}does @{ui}have an @{b}lzx/lha/lzh@{ub} suffix(@{b}lzh@{ub}
	is  @{b}de-archived@{ub}  by @{b}LhA@{ub}).  Added  detection  to  check  firstly if  the
	alternate  path  for  '@{b}l2z@{ub}'  exists  and secondly that it  is the  full
	pathname.

@{h "2.4"}	@{b}LZH@{ub} archives now  processed fully as if they  were normal @{b}LhA@{ub} archives.
	Found  a much nicer  line to  clear  the screen for the final  @{b}Thankyou@{ub}
	message ( from an old Amiga Power coverdisk!).  Extra options  added to
	the @{b}LhA/LZX@{ub} command line to give @{b}faster progress display@{ub} and @{b}suffixing@{ub}.
	Added extra @{b}ANSI@{ub} line "@{fg shine}*e[0 p@{fg text}" which supposedly turns off the cursor to
	make text output twice as fast, so @{b}LZX@{ub} etc. can now work faster.  Empty
	directories  now dealt with  and @{b}de/-archived@{ub} as usual,  although there
	seems to be a @{"bug" link Bugs 19} in @{b}LZX@{ub} here -  luckily this seems to in no way affect
	the running of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

	Also added a similar routine to that of the default path of the archive
	when using @{bl "LhA2LZX"} for multiple  archives (see @{"v2.2" link Hist2 46})  to have a default
	path for where '@{b}l2z@{ub}' is stored, in case the user doesn't have much @{b}RAM:@{ub}
	(and so won't want to go  searching through drawers each time they want
	to have '@{b}l2z@{ub}' somewhere on their hard-drive).

@{h "2.5"}	Added 2 small routines just to check that both the @{b}path@{ub} and the @{b}archive@{ub}
	exist when selected,  in case the user decides to @{b}type in@{ub} either.  Also
	improved the "@{b}Convert to . . ?@{ub}"requester to show @{i}exactly @{ui} what filetype
	you are  converting and what you  can convert it to.  This makes things
	much  easier  to see  (in terms  of options),  and  also shows  off the
	ability of @{b}filetype detection@{ub} more.

	Also fixed  a small  bug in  the  @{b}Insufficient Memory@{ub}  area to do  with
	quotes and volume names with spaces in, such as @{fg shine}Ram Disk:@{fg text}. Filenames or
	volume names with spaces need to be surrounded by quotation marks, like
	this:
		"@{fg shine}Ram Disk:@{fg text}"
	so they can be accessed -if you just type @{fg shine}Ram Disk:@{fg text} in a Shell,AmigaDOS
	will try to  run the command @{fg fill}Ram@{fg text}.  Now the path name of the archive can
	have spaces in.

@{h "2.6"}	@{b}First official release@{ub} (on my web page)
	As the  keyfile  for @{b}LZX@{ub} is now  freely available on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub},  extra
	features of @{b}LZX@{ub} are enabled, such as de-archiving of @{b}LhA/LZH@{ub} files,with
	a @{b}25-30%@{ub} speed increase.  Also is the option of faster archiving at the
	cost of 32k of RAM. I have included both of these here to  increase the
	overall  speed of  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.  I tried here to  fix the tilde  @{"bug" link Bugs 49},  but
	without much success.  Expect better handling in the next release!

@{h "2.6a"}	@{b}First AmiNET upload@{ub}
	All I did here was shorten  the length of the  program by renaming  the
	variables with the prefix "nl2z",  which is unique enough for me to use
	@{fg shine}list@{fg text} to generate a list of the  variables at the end and use this in  a
	script created by  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  to delete them all.   I got this idea  from
	reading  the  startup-sequence  (it uses  the same  principle  but runs
	monitor drivers).  I also changed  the command that  clears the  output
	screen at the end to make sure it will work on @{b}KS2.0@{ub}.

@{h "2.7"}	This version now contains filename error trapping,  and fixes the tilde
	@{"bug" link Bugs 49} for  the moment.  If a tilde is detected in the filename,  an error
	message is  produced and  the program quits.  I am currently  trying to
	think of a way round this without quitting the program or have the user
	typing an  apostrophe before  the tilde themselves,  but I really don't
	know  of a way to get  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} to scan filenames and insert  specified
	characters before other characters :^( , and I don't really want to use
	@{"AREXX" LINK "AREXX"}  or an actual  program to do this as  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  is not just a file
	conversion utility, it is an exercise in @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub},showing its potential
	and all  that it can do.

	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} now skips to the  end  and deletes all  variables currently made
	if @{b}LhA@{ub} or @{b}LZX@{ub} cannot be found, instead of just quitting.

	As the @{b}registered@{ub} version of @{b}LZX@{ub} is now needed,  a quick check is  now
	performed to see if the @{b}lzx.keyfile@{ub} exists,as otherwise @{b}LZX@{ub} won't work.

@{h "2.7a"}	It seems that the change  to de-archiving  with @{b}LZX@{ub} instead of @{b}LhA@{ub}  has
	revealed a bug in the @{b}68000@{ub} version of @{b}LZX@{ub},  which seems to ignore some
	of the command line options for  de-archiving,  or at least not process
	them correctly as the  @{b}68020@{ub} version does.  The filename of the archive
	is given to @{b}LZX@{ub},but the '@{b}000@{ub} version adds the suffix ".lzx" to the file
	even if is specifically told not to. This means it cannot find the file
	(because it is looking for "@{fg shine}myarc.lha.lzx@{fg text}" instead of "@{fg shine}myarc.lha@{fg text}"), and
	so it returns a @{b}Return Code@{ub} of @{b}10@{ub}.  If there is a user-abort,  a @{b}Return
	Code@{ub} of @{b}20@{ub} occurs (Return Codes are values passed back from programs to
	indicate the result of an operation -  such as successful, fail, user -
	abort and so on),which is what @{bl "LhA2LZX"} checks for,as I found previously
	nasty things happened if a user aborted the program (ie the archive was
	deleted).  I tried to also check for this @{b}RC@{ub} of @{b}10@{ub}, but found that when
	checking a @{b}Return Code@{ub} only one could be checked.  Knowing already that
	a @{b}0 @{ub} is returned if the  operation is successful, I  altered the @{b}Return
	Code@{ub} checking line to inversely check - ie check that the operation was
	@{I}not @{UI} successful, and act accordingly.  This would mean that if anything
	went wrong (ie something that had not happened during my tests),@{bl "LhA2LZX"}
	should compensate and Do The Right Thing, even if I had not anticipated
	the problem or even known about it.Now @{bl "LhA2LZX"} pops up an error message
	requester telling you of the problem, and  then skips to the "More...?"
	requester.  Your archive should remain intact,  although not converted,
	and will not  be deleted as it  would previously have been.  If you are
	using  an '@{b}020@{ub} or higher, you will  probably never see  this requester.

	I also  changed part of  the @{b}LZX@{ub} command line as a  result of this (the
	@{b}LZX@{ub} command line refers to the line of  code in @{bl "LhA2LZX"} in which @{b}LZX@{ub} is
	started and various commands and options are passed to it -for instance
	what  the  archive  name is,  whether to  archive  everything in  sub -
	directories and so on). I changed the -X option to -X0, which would not
	automatically  append the suffix ".lzx" to the  archive filename - this
	seems to change nothing if using the '@{b}020@{ub} version (as long as you don't
	delete the  suffix in the requester, but you wouldn't do this anyway as
	you can  just click on the filename), but if using the '@{b}000@{ub}  version it
	will return an error. Strangely, the error returned is "Bad LZX archive
	header" - not surprising because it is operating on an @{b}LhA@{ub} archive! The
	'@{b}020@{ub} version handles @{b}LhA@{ub} files the same as @{b}LZX@{ub} files. It seems that the
	'@{b}000@{ub}  version  in the @{b}LZX@{ub}  distribution  doesn't  have  the  registered
	features...

	I had a cunning  idea  to use the @{b}Version@{ub}  command  to determine  which
	version of @{b}LZX@{ub} is being used, but the only version information given by
	@{b}LZX@{ub} is the version number.There are other ways of finding which version
	(like checking the size of the @{b}LZX@{ub} executable using List or something),
	and changing the command line accordingly(ie using @{b}LhA@{ub} to de-archive on
	an '@{b}000@{ub}), but then how  many people with '@{b}000s@{ub} nowadays would be  using
	this program?  Thus I have decided that @{bl "LhA2LZX"} now requires an '@{b}020@{ub} or
	faster CPU, as this is what most have nowadays.If you're still using an
	'@{b}000@{ub}, write to me (snail-mail or e-mail)and I'll send you a version for
	it.

	Another small change was just putting the path of @{b}LhA@{ub} and @{b}LZX@{ub} in speech
	marks, just in case your path has  a space in (like if you keep them in
	"@{fg shine}Workbench 3.0@{fg text}" or something).

	I shall also note that @{bl "LhA2LZX"} supports filecomments  and filedates and
	so on of the files in the original archive -this means all comments etc
	will stay  intact when  converted between the  two archive types.  I am
	told not all the programs similar to @{bl "LhA2LZX"} do this (although that may
	change after the other authors' read this...).

@{h "2.7b"}	Not  much change  here  in terms  of code,  but a  bit  in  ideas.  The
	suggestion  came  from  @{b}Mosquito@{ub},  and it  seemed  like a  good idea to
	implement.  The file comment, creation date and time of the new archive
	are replaced by the old - so the only noticable difference between your
	archives  is the  file type and the  file size  (and the name slightly,
	obviously!).  Thus all file comments of the archives remain intact, and
	the  old date  used makes it  look as  if  it was  the new  archive you
	downloaded/created  in the  first  place!   This was all done  by using
	features of the @{b}List@{ub} command - showing just how versatile it is!

	Another tiny detail was changed - after converting to the other archive
	type, I used the suffix .(lha|lzx) (lha @{b}or@{ub} lzx) to copy the new archive
	over and get its size:I used this format because you were converting to
	the other file type, which could have been lha->lzx or lzx->lha.  Since
	writing that line I had added  another variable somewhere along the way
	which would give the  other file type suffix ($nsuf),  so I altered the
	line to give the  other suffix,  instead of either  because I could now
	determine which you had converted it to.

@{h "2.8"}	Well,  I seemed  to  change a  lot around  in this  release!   Not much
	difference in operation, but in efficiency.  I noticed that much of the
	code was repeating itself throughout (mainly the area where @{b}LhA@{ub} and @{b}LZX@{ub}
	were  used,  and  the  @{b}Insufficient  Memory@{ub}  bit,  and  also  the  size
	comparisons of the old and new archives, as well as a few other areas).
	I was able to cut a lot of this out and make much of the code common to
	whichever operation was being carried out,  thus making the whole thing
	much more efficient,  and it looks a lot more streamlined too!  It is a
	worthwhile job to compare this version with @{"v2.7b" link Hist2 231},  and see exactly how
	and where I have  steamlined it.  Part of the fact that there was a lot
	of similar code was  that before @{"v2.6" link Hist2 136},  @{b}LhA@{ub} was used to  de-archive LhA
	archives,  whereas now  @{b}LZX@{ub}  is used to  de-archive  both file  types -
	meaning this bit is common to both  de-archiving processes and can thus
	be put  into a  single process.  Using the  same code  like this  to do
	several processes (the same code is used  whether you are converting to
	the other file type  or to the smaller archive,  and this is only taken
	into account at the end when deciding whether or not to replace the old
	archive) is a @{b}GOOD THING@{ub} when writing code...of course,  I never should
	have  programmed it  like  that  in the  first  place...:^)...but, hey,
	that's what I'm at University to learn...:^)

	I managed to get the file size of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} down to around @{b}10k@{ub} from @{b}15k@{ub} -
	which shows just how well I  did in optimising it!   I then added a few
	more  comments  though, which  increased  the size.  Without  comments,
	@{bl "LhA2LZX"}  is about half the size.  I decided to  use this  as a separate
	release to show  how effectively you can  sometimes improve a script by
	making very small changes in the way it works,but large ones in the way
	it is written.

	The only differences you may notice about this new version  (apart from
	maybe some things being executed in a different order)  is firstly that
	you no longer have to enter the path of the  drawer the archive is in -
	you can  just select  the  archive  itself  -  and  secondly  that  the
	destination of '@{b}l2z@{ub}' is now saved forever in  @{b}ENVARC@{ub}: so  that whenever
	you run @{bl "LhA2LZX"} after the first time, you won't have to choose where to
	create  it,   which  saves  time  and   hassle,   unless  you  get  the
	@{b}Insufficient Memory@{ub}  requester,  in which  case you get to choose a new
	location  for it,  which is  then  saved in  place of the  original.  I
	changed  this because  that  damn  "@{b}Where should I store...@{ub}"  requester
	popped up  every  single  time I  wanted to  convert an  archive, and I
	always chose @{b}RAM@{ub}:,  so it seemed pointless  and time-wasting to have to
	choose  each time  the same  drawer.  If you  ever want  to change  the
	destination for '@{b}l2z@{ub}',  just delete @{b}ENV:LhA2LZXl2zpath@{ub} and  run @{bl "LhA2LZX"}
	again to choose another drawer. With the "@{b}Select the drawer the archive
	is in...@{ub}" bit: I always found selecting the  drawer and  then getting a
	requester to select the  file was a  bit long-winded, but  I thought it
	wasn't  too bad  if you  were converting  several files  from the  same
	drawer, as the drawer of the first archive was used as the default  for
	the following  archives.  I found that using  another option  in @{b}List@{ub} I
	was able  to get the path of  the drawer by  simply stripping  away the
	filename,  which made things easier  and less time-consuming.  Is there
	nothing that this command won't do?

	Another  minor alteration:  I changed  the  output in the  @{b}Insufficient
	Memory@{ub}  part to tell you how much memory in  Kilobytes instead of bytes
	you may need,  as it's much easier to read and relate to like this.  If
	you ever get the requester,  the archive must be  fairly big and so the
	large number  telling you how many  bytes of memory you  may need won't
	mean much (I always found myself mentally inserting the commas!).

	I changed  a few of the  '@{b}Skip@{ub}'s to  skip  to different places I think,
	just so it would  make a bit more sense when using it ... however, as I
	was working on  this version  I was also  working on a parallel version
	for use  within @{bl "DOpus"} which  would take an archive  name at the command
	line so  that you  could select  an archive in a @{bl "DOpus"} lister and  then
	click on an  @{bl "LhA2LZX"} button...and before I knew it,  it started rapidly
	blossoming into the magnificently improved... @{" " LINK Hist3 4}

@EndNode

@Node "Hist3" "Program History & Development - v3.x"
@Prev "Hist2"
@Next "Fut"

@{bd "Program History - v3.x"}

@{h "3.0"}	Where to begin?!   @{bl "LhA2LZX"} now  accepts  multiple files  for input, can
	repack an  archive to ensure  minimum size for  an archive type and can
	successfully be used in @{bl "DOpus"} to select multiple files and work on them
	sequentially!  It  now  creates  several  scripts  of  its  own  whilst
	running,  and  executes  itself from  these scripts!  I shall  explain:
	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} will check to  see on startup if any archives  have been passed
	to it for processing (which it  will have been if you are using it from
	@{bl "DOpus"}), and if none have been given then a requester pops up asking you
	to select  one or  more archives  for processing.  It then lists  these
	archives into another  script - for example this new script would read:

	@{fg shine}execute "DH1:Toolsdaemon/lha2lzx/LhA2LZX" "AQ2:Temp/AGHTW.LZX"
	execute "DH1:Toolsdaemon/lha2lzx/LhA2LZX" "AQ2:Temp/AIFFdt.LhA"
	execute "DH1:Toolsdaemon/lha2lzx/LhA2LZX" "AQ2:Temp/AnimGIF.LZX"@{fg text}

	and then this new script would be executed.   As you can see, each line
	gives  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  an  archive to  process, and once it  has processed the
	first it will move onto the second, and so on.  If @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is  given an
	archive on startup like this,  it will process only this archive before
	quitting.  This script  is created using a neat  little function of the
	multi-talented @{b}List@{ub} - telling it exactly  how you want it to output the
	filenames it is given.  You can  see also that the path of  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  is
	given - this is saved as an env variable using the new installer script
	and so will change to wherever @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is stored.

	This  version also saw  a neat  little trick  concerning @{b}LZH@{ub} archives -
	renaming  them  with  an .lha  suffix, as  they're basically  the  same
	anyway, and can be processed as if they are LhA archives.

	I've also  made sure  that every  time a  drawer name  or file name  is
	passed as an argument it is surrounded by  quotes just in case it has a
	space in, like "@{fg shine}Ram Disk:@{fg text}".

	Another new  neat feature  is that of  "@{b}Repack@{ub}"  -  an archive  will be
	de-archived  and then  re-archived to ensure that, if you want to  keep
	the archive as the same file type, it is of the minimum size.  This was
	achieved simply by adding about @{b}5@{ub} lines of code!  All I did was to swap
	the  contents  of the  variables concerning  the suffixes  (so that @{b}LhA@{ub}
	changed to @{b}LZX@{ub} and vice versa) before  the file is de-archived, so that
	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} thinks  the file  is of  the other  type when re-archiving, and
	hence re-archives  it with the  appropriate program!  The suffixes  are
	then swapped back.  Simple but effective!  I added  this option because
	when using @{bl "DOpus"} to  select files to put in an archive,  the individual
	filenames are  passed to  @{b}LhA@{ub}/@{b}LZX@{ub}, and if you have many files  it often
	creates the archive with the first few files, then adds the next few in
	a  separate command, and  then the  next few  and so  on.  This  rarely
	affects @{b}LhA@{ub}  archive creation,  but @{b}LZX@{ub} archives  are often reduced  in
	size if all files are added  in one go  -  in other words by a @{b}wildcard@{ub}
	pattern.  This is achieved by @{bl "LhA2LZX"} doing what it  has always done  -
	@{b}de-archiving@{ub} to a newly created temporary  drawer and then @{b}re-archiving@{ub}
	everything inside to a new archive.

	@{fg fill}DOpus@{fg text} archive creation:
	@{fg shine}lzx -e -3 -F a "RAM:lha2lzx2" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX.guide.info"
	"lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.6" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.6a" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.5"
	"lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.4" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.3" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.2"
	"lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.1" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.0" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v1.2"
	"lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v1.1" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX.guide" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.7b"
	"lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.7" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.7a" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX_v2.8"
	"lha2lzx/LhA2LZX.install" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX.info"
	lzx -e -3 -F a "RAM:lha2lzx2" "lha2lzx/LhA2LZX.install.info"
	"lha2lzx2.readme"@{fg text}

	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} archive repacking:
	@{fg shine}lzx -e -3 -F a l2z/#?@{fg text}

	You  can  see  that the  archive is  first  created  by giving all  the
	filenames to add, but the command line is too long and so LZX is called
	again to add the rest of the files.  Once the archive has been created,
	it can be easily repacked by a wildcard pattern,  which is often better
	due to the nature of how @{"LZX" LINK "LZX"} works over @{"LhA" LINK "LhA"}.

	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} is extensively commented now  - almost every line in fact!  You
	can now follow exactly  what is going on line by line,  and if you want
	to get the full benefit  then read it as it is executing  -  so you can
	see what is being created, what it says and so on.

	The final line  "@{b}Quit@{ub}" was  removed, otherwise the  whole process would
	quit after  processing the first archive, when the  script reached that
	line of execution.  I moved the "@{b}Thanks for using...@{ub}" farewell  message
	too (as otherwise  it would appear after every  archive conversion) and
	it is  now only  reached  at the end of  the  entire process,  when all
	archives  have been  processed.  If using from  @{bl "DOpus"},  all output like
	this is suppressed,  as it looks better without it there.  If you still
	want to see  the files being  de-archived,  set the  "@{b}Output to window"@{ub}
	flag.

	Almost all of  the '@{b}Skip@{ub}'s have been altered to  -  instead of skipping
	back  for you to  enter another  filename if the one  you gave  doesn't
	exist, it skips to the end.  This is because the  filename you gave  it
	is now  integrated into  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, and so  after telling you  it doesn't
	exist it  will check  to see  if a  filename has  been entered  already
	before asking you for another - and since one  @{I}has @{UI}been entered, you'll
	get stuck in a loop.  The only time you will ever  encounter this is if
	you enter a file's name that  doesn't exist, and the only way you could
	do this would be to enter it by the @{b}CLI@{ub}.  But seeing as the whole point
	of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  is for you to use  it by the  requesters or now from @{bl "DOpus"},
	it'll never happen :^) .  The same  would have happened if the file was
	not an @{b}LhA@{ub} or @{b}LZX@{ub} archive, but  I changed that too so  that if the file
	you give it is not an archive, @{bl "LhA2LZX"} skips to process the next one.

	The @{"backtick" LINK Hist2 82} is once  again put to clever use.  The executable  archive
	listing file @{fg shine}RAM:LhA2LZX.exe@{fg text}  is created by passing the filenames given
	from the file requester into  @{b}List@{ub}, which then outputs the filenames as
	you saw @{"above" LINK Hist3 15}, ready for processing.  You can see this @{"here" link LhA2LZX/Main 120}.

	The four programs  originally  loaded into memory at the  start are now
	checked to see if they are already in memory,  in which case they won't
	need to  be reloaded,  and so aren't.  This just makes  things a little
	tidier, and also uses the @{"backtick" LINK Hist2 82} effectively.

@{h "3.0a"}	I found a much neater way of  getting the path of @{bl "LhA2LZX"},  meaning you
	don't need to install it now - it can be easily run  from anywhere.  In
	fact,  I found 2 ways:  the second way was  much more efficient and did
	exactly the same job.  Here were my notes for the first way:

	@{fg shine}echo `cd` >env:LhA2LZXpath NOLINE@{fg text}						;This gets the current directory (i.e. the drawer of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}), e.g. "dh1:Temp"
	@{fg shine}echo "$LhA2LZXpath" FIRST 256 LEN 1 >env:nl2zpathtmp NOLINE@{fg text}	;This will get the last character of the drawer - if it is ":" then it is a root directory...
	@{fg shine}if $nl2zpathtmp EQ :@{fg text}								;...and if it is...
		@{fg shine}echo "LhA2LZX" >>env:LhA2LZXpath NOLINE@{fg text}				;...we only echo "LhA2LZX" onto the end of the directory name...
	@{fg shine}else@{fg text}												;...otherwise...
		@{fg shine}echo "/LhA2LZX" >>env:LhA2LZXpath NOLINE@{fg text}			;...we have to make sure we go into the directory where @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is
	@{fg shine}endif@{fg text}											;This first section joins the drawer of where @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is found to the actual @{bl "LhA2LZX"} file e.g. "dh1:Temp/LhA2LZX". This first part of the program merely gets the command line of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, and stores it in 'env:LhA2LZXpath'

	At the  beginning,  the current directory is echoed to a file, and then
	"LhA2LZX" is appended to that, depending on whether it a root directory
	or not  (just read the comments  for more  info).   I decided to submit
	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} for inclusion on an Amiga Format cover CD and found it would be
	a  little clumsy  having to specify  the path on there of @{bl "LhA2LZX"},  and
	then suddenly had  an idea  of how to get the  command path on  startup
	instead, meaning you can run it from anywhere without having to install
	it  first.  Below is a paragraph which was intended after @{"v3.0" link Hist3 4}  for the
	next version of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, but is now no longer needed:

	"As the path of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is now known, a small check is performed at the
	start just to  make sure it is there.  I kept  forgetting to change the
	path  back  to my  original  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  drawer  when testing  the install
	script,  and after I deleted  the newly installed  version  it wouldn't
	work from my original drawer  (as the path  specified by the  installer
	had just been deleted)."

	This also helps to explain why the new process is better.  The check is
	still there, but  you will now  only experience  it if you run  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}
	from the CLI and don't CD to the drawer @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is in beforehand.

	The  "@{fg shine}echo "$LhA2LZXpath" FIRST 256 LEN 1@{fg text}"  line  will  give  the  last
	character  of the  current directory by starting at the last  character
	and echoing  it out - it takes the  first character to start echoing as
	character number 256,  but as this is the maximum length of a  filename
	anyway you won't  in all probability  have this many characters  in the
	filename and so it starts echoing at the last character in the filename.
	This will either give us ":"  (for a root directory, e.g. RAM:) or  the
	last  character  of the  directory  (e.g. "p" for dh1:Temp).   This  is
	important, because when we echo "LhA2LZX" we need to know if we have to
	descend into a directory first (i.e. echo "/LhA2LZX").  The filename of
	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} is concatenated  (joined)  onto the directory  to give the full
	command  path of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.  This is done by using the double redirection
	symbol >>. This means that the text to be echoed is echoed into the end
	of the file specified without replacing the file with the new text:

	e.g.

	@{fg shine}echo "Hello" NOLINE >env:new@{fg text}
	@{fg shine}echo " World" >>env:new@{fg text}

	The file env:new now reads thus:

	@{fg shine}Hello World@{fg text}

	The @{b}NOLINE@{ub}  keyword tells  @{b}Echo@{ub} not to put a carriage return at the end
	of the line of input text, so we can keep everything on one line.

	I then  realised that there  was a much  easier way to  get the command
	line of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} using just one line instead of 7:

	@{fg shine}list LhA2LZX LFORMAT=%F%N >env:LhA2LZXpath@{fg text}

	As you will already be in the current directory of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  (there is a
	check that  warns you if you  are not, before quitting), I was  able to
	just use @{b}List@{ub} to list the full pathname of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.  %F gives  the disk
	and directory name, and %N gives the filename.

	I have not included  @{"v3.0" link Hist3 4} in this  archive because it only differs from
	@{b}v3.0a@{ub} by not  having the  first 3  lines  of the  actual program (which
	includes the @{b}List@{ub}  line above), and  also it has a  small check at  the
	beginning to see if @{bl "LhA2LZX"} has been installed correctly:

	@{fg shine}if NOT EXISTS env:LhA2LZXpath@{fg text}			;This checks to see if the path of the location of where @{bl "LhA2LZX"} is stored on disk has been saved to the file 'env:LhA2LZXpath', which is done in the installation process
		@{fg shine}RequestChoice >nil: "LhA2LZX Error Message" "LhA2LZX not installed using the installer script!*nSee docs for details!" "Quit"
		quit@{fg text}							;If the file isn't there, there's no point in carrying on...
	@{fg shine}endif@{fg text}

	Now, if the path file does not exist then it is created.

@{h "3.1"}	This version sees much better  handling of the tilde @{"bug" link Bugs 49}, by use of an
	@{"AREXX" LINK "AREXX"} script.  AmigaDOS checks for a  tilde in the filename as before,
	but if it finds one then it starts the AREXX script @{"lha2lzx.rexx" link REXX:lha2lzx.rexx/MAIN} which
	searches  through the  filename and  inserts an apostrophe before  each
	tilde - so that the  AmigaDOS program Rename can be  used to rename the
	file  with underscores  instead of  tilde's.  The file  will be renamed
	even if you do not perform any actions on it. I'm still learning AREXX, 
	so in the future I will probably use this  for checking if the new file
	will fit on the destination  disk.  @{"lha2lzx.rexx" link REXX:lha2lzx.rexx/MAIN} will fail  if the path
	of the archive contains spaces, but then you shouldn't really have them
	there in the first place :^)

	I also  found that  I'd got 2 env  variables which  contained the  same
	information (nl2zldfl1 and nl2zl), so I got rid of the former  by using
	the latter in its place.

@{h "3.2"}	The docs always  take longer to write than the actual  program, so  I'm
	going to keep  this short :^).  On the AmigaDOS  side of things,  all I
	did was get the protection bits of the old archive and transfer them to
	the new,  use a small program 'inf' to get the remaining amount of disk
	space on the destination  (so now if your new archive is too big to fit
	back  over the  old archive,  a requester pops up telling  you this and
	asking you where you want the new archive to be saved to), and check if
	LhA and/or LZX are resident and use the resident ones if they are.  The
	big improvement to this version  (apart from the remaining  destination
	size)was done by adding to the ever-growing @{"AREXX" link Arexx} script, @{"lha2lzx.rexx" link REXX:lha2lzx.rexx/MAIN}.
	This  does  3 new  things: it  alters  the  filecomment  if it has  any
	asterisks in (it changes them to plus signs, because previously if your
	filecomment  ended with an  asterisk then in the command line  it would
	have read  "<comment>*", and AmigaDOS interprets  the asterisk followed
	by a quote  character to  mean "include the following quote  character,
	don't  treat it as the end  of the argument"),  it removes the unwanted
	Line Feed  and  Carriage Return  characters  from  the end of the  file
	created by 'inf' which gives  the size of  the  remaining disk space on
	the destination disk,  so that the  file can be used as an env variable
	for use with @{b}Eval@{ub}),  and  it takes the protection  bits of the original
	archive  and gets rid  of any hyphens that it may  contain so that only
	the actual protection bits remain - e.g. if you type

	@{fg shine}list ram:disk.info LFORMAT=%A@{fg text}

	you will get an output of the protection bits of the file, like

	@{fg fill}----rw-d@{fg text}

	-  the  protection  bits  tell  you  whether  the  file  is  deletable,
	executable  and so on  -  just select the icon and choose "Information"
	from the  "Icons" menu,  and look at the check boxes in the upper right
	of the newly-appeared window.   If you want to set  these bits from the
	CLI, you have to use the @{b}Protect@{ub} command:

	@{fg shine}protect ram:disk.info arwe@{fg text}

	This  would  set the bits for  "Archived",  "Readable",  "Writable" and
	"Executable".  As you can see, there are no hyphens as @{b}List@{ub} gives,  and
	if you try the following command you will get an error:

	@{fg shine}protect ram:disk.info --arwe-@{fg text}

	You cannot have hyphens  in the @{b}Protect@{ub} command line,  which means that
	if you want to set them using the output from @{b}List@{ub}, you have to get rid
	of the hyphens in some way  -  all I did in  the AREXX script was to go
	through each character in the output individually and check if it was a
	protection bit like "a" or "d", and add that letter to an output string
	which was then written to a file.

	The protection bits are:

	@{fg shine}H - Hidden
	S - Script
	P - Pure
	A - Archived
	R - Readable
	W - Writable
	E - Executable
	D - Deletable@{fg text}

	@{"Frank Bunton" link Thanks}  once again deserves  a mention here for his help with the
	AREXX  -  firstly for his excellent "AREXX For Beginners", and secondly
	for  giving  some  advice on parts  of the  procedures  and Good  AREXX
	Programming (TM)!

	Didn't do much of a good job keeping this bit short, did I?  ;^)

@{h "3.2a"}	Just a little housekeeping with this release to make it a little easier
	to  use:  I  changed   all   occurences   of   @{fg shine}echo   "*e[1;1H*eJ"@{fg text}   to
	@{fg shine}echo "*e[0;0H*e[J"@{fg text},  as I had  problems  with the display  not clearing
	properly due  to the scrolling nature of  KingCON.  Now whether you are
	using  KingCON or not to enhance your Shell, the window will be cleared
	between operations.  The only other thing  I have changed is the format
	of these "Program History" pages so that they're not as  sprawling, and
	also I added  an extra little bit of code  that gives the difference of
	filesizes in kb instead of bytes  if it is over 10k, so it is easier to
	relate to.  I may put  this into the @{"lha2lzx.rexx" link REXX:lha2lzx.rexx/MAIN} file as  this code is
	repetitive, and can easily be simplified in @{"AREXX" link Arexx}.



	This .guide has also been extensively added to...although you  may have
	to search for  some of the  @{b}hidden@{ub}  pages...as a treat for everyone who
	has got this far,why don't you have a small break and go on my treasure
	hunt by double-clicking on the word "hidden" above...
@Endnode

@node "hidden" "Hidden pages?  Surely not..."
@Next "Thanks"
So you think there are some hidden pages, eh?  I always liked treasure
hunts...

@{b}Clue One:	The power of AmigaGuides is detailed in Frank Bunton's "How To
		Write An Amigaguide" ...the most comprehensive document on the
		subject...isn't he on the "Thanks to..." page...?@{ub}

@endnode


