Snail-mail:	c/o	37 Woodside Gardens
				RAVENSHEAD
				NOTTINGHAM
				NG15 9GF
				UK

E-mail is preferred if possible (but don't expect a reply during the Summer
 months ... :^) ... and that means  June - September for all you Southern -
 Hemispherists...).

If writing by snail-mail, please include a stamped addressed envelope.
As I was once told..."We don't get paid for writing this, you know!"

@{bl "LhA2LZX"} is @{b}GIFTWARE@{ub}.  That means if you use it,  send me a little something.
It doesn't matter if it's a  nice picture by e-mail,  a link to a web site I
might like, or even a 20p bar of chocolate (@{b}Mint@{ub}'s my favourite...). I don't
care, as long as I know you are appreciating my small gift to you :^)


You can download the latest version from my @{bl "LhA2LZX"} web page:
@{i}http://www-student.lboro.ac.uk/~corb1/lha2lzx.html @{ui}
@Endnode

@node "Sarah" "A secret page dedicated to the wonderful...Sarah McLachlan!"

@{bg highlight}Sarah McLachlan - she's great!@{bg background}

Behold the second hidden page!  Just thought I'd add a bit of info about one
of my absolute favourite singer/songwriters.  Bet you weren't expecting
this!

Sarah McLachlan is a Canadian songstress with the most beautiful voice this
side of the Moon. In the @{fg shine}1998 Grammy Awards@{fg text} she was nominated in @{b}3@{ub} categories:

@{fg shine}Best Female Pop Vocal Performance@{fg text} 	for @{b}Building A Mystery@{ub}
@{fg shine}Best Pop Instrumental Performance@{fg text} 	for @{b}Last Dance@{ub}
@{fg shine}Best Pop Album@{fg text} 				for @{b}Surfacing@{ub}

and she won the first @{b}2@{ub}.  Go Sarah!

 
She has released @{b}7@{ub} albums so far:

@{b}Touch@{ub}	@{fg fill}1988@{fg text}		Recorded when she was only 19!

@{b}Solace@{ub}	@{fg fill}1991@{fg text}		Has some wonderful tracks, especially for those quiet
				moments.

@{b}Fumbling@{ub}			Loads of the songs from here have been on "Due South",
@{b}Towards@{ub}	@{fg fill}1993@{fg text}		an excellent TV series about a Canadian Mountie. This is
@{b}Ecstacy@{ub}			great to listen to on those dark, cold, long winter
				nights!

@{b}The@{ub}				Sarah and her crew decided one night, after drinking
@{b}Freedom@{ub}	@{fg fill}1995@{fg text}		loads of red wine, to go into someone's basement and
@{b}Sessions@{ub}			re-record "@{b}Fumbling@{ub}..." as it originally sounded - much
				more acoustic.  The sound of Sarah's vocals with just
				her guitar or piano is just breathtaking! And if that
				isn't enough, it's an @{b}enhanced@{ub} multimedia CD as well as
				an album, so if you can run Quicktime movies you can
				see video interviews, and all the videos to all the
				songs from her first @{b}3@{ub} albums!  Bargain!				

@{b}Rarities,@{ub}			I only got this Canada-only release recently, so I'm
@{b}B-Sides,@{ub}	@{fg fill}1996@{fg text}		still listening to it. Some of the songs are great!
@{b}and Other@{ub}
@{b}Stuff@{ub}

@{b}Surfacing@{ub}	@{fg fill}1997@{fg text}		I've got this one playing at the moment! It's great. And
				it's an enhanced multimedia CD too, with more interviews
				and live versions of some of the songs and stuff.

@{b}Live@{ub}		@{fg fill}19??@{fg text}		Haven't got this yet.  It's one of her earlier concerts,
				put on CD.  Go to my life.html page to listen
				to a live RealAudio concert lasting an hour!


So now you know a lot more about Sarah and her albums than you used to. If
anybody remembers what songs she performed on "Later...with Jools Holland"
last time she was on ('93/'94 I think), I'd be grateful for any info (it's
probably only people in the UK that have seen this, though...).

I've told you about @{b}Sarah@{ub}, but should I even @{I}start @{UI}on the marvellous @{b}Lisa@{ub}?

If you want any more info about Sarah and others, go to my Music Emporium:
@{fg shine}http://www-student.lboro.ac.uk/~corb1/music.html@{fg text}
where you can find links, audio files, movie files, an hour-long RealAudio
concert and more!


@{b}Clue Three:	Which wonderful singer have I not even @{I}started @{UI}telling you
			about?@{ub}
@endnode

@Node "Also" "Also by the Author"
@Prev "Author"
@Next "Index"

@{bd "Also by the Author"}

All the programs below are @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} @{"script" link Scripts} files created purely to show what
you can achieve,using the software you already have,to make your life easier.
Most of them are simply "front-end" programs to @{"CLI" link CLI} executables- so you just
click requesters instead of typing out @{b}CLI@{ub} commands like in @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

@{h "AllowBad.req"}
	Do you have @{b}floppies@{ub} with  @{b}hard errors@{ub} on?  Do you find that you simply
	can't @{b}format@{ub} them or @{b}use them properly@{ub}? Then @{b}wipe@{ub} away your @{b}tears@{ub},  for
	@{b}AllowBad.req@{ub}  is  here!   A   simple  requester  interface  to  @{i}Mikolaj 
	Calusinski's@{ui} @{b}AllowBad@{ub} means  you  too  can now live  with the  peace of
	mind that never again will you have a @{b}Bad Floppy! ®@{ub}
@{h "DMSMaker"}
	A fab little @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} script file  allowing you to use all the standard
	functions of the @{b}DiskMasher@{ub} System - including read, write, view, test,
	repack,  and even encrypt  your  @{b}DMS@{ub}  files with an invisible password!
@{h "DSQView"}
	A small file  which  finds the  filelist in a  @{"DiskSqueeze" link WhatUse 12}  archive and
	displays it.
@{h "FillDisk"}
	Helps fill disks to their maximum, using @{i}Torbjörn Hultén's @{ui}"@{b}Fill v2.0.@{ub}"
	Choose your files by requester, and  @{b}Fill@{ub}  calculates which combination
	of files to  use to fill the  disk to its maximum.  Useful for storage.
@{h "HappySearch"}
	I once had a  @{b}virus@{ub}  which adds itself  to every file you open,  and is
	recognisable by finding "@{b}Happy New Year 96!@{ub}" in your files. HappySearch
	will search specified files to see if you have the virus.
@{h "LhAMaker"}
	This creates @{b}LhA@{ub} archives from  specified input files,  via requesters.
@{h "UnLZXer"}
	This de-archives @{b}LZX@{ub} archives to a chosen destination.

You can download these from my @{bl "LhA2LZX"} web page.
@Endnode

@Node "Arc" "Archiving"
@Next "De-arc"
@Prev "Index"

@{bd "Archiving"}

@{b}Archiving@{ub}  means  to  backup  files. In the case of @{b}LhA@{ub} & @{b}LZX@{ub}, all the files
you  wish  to  backup  -@{i}store  a copy somewhere in case you need them in the
future  to, for example, replace lost data @{ui}-are merged into one @{b}archive@{ub} file
and  @{b}compressed@{ub}, so that in almost all cases the final @{b}archive@{ub} file takes up
less space than the files which were @{b}archived@{ub} did.

See also @{" De-archiving " link De-arc}

@{b}NB@{ub}	"De-/archiving" in this document refers to when @{bl "LhA2LZX"} @{b}de-archives@{ub} and
	then @{b}archives@{ub} an archive.
@Endnode

@Node "De-arc" "De-archiving"
@Next "AREXX"
@Prev "Arc"

@{bd "De-archiving"}

@{b}De-archiving@{ub}  means  to  restore  files  from  a  backup  archive. Files are
@{b}decompressed@{ub} and separated back to individual files.

See also @{" Archiving " link Arc}
@Endnode

@node "Arexx"
@Next "CLI"
@Prev "De-arc"

@{b}AREXX@{ub}  is an  interpreted  programming  language  -  which  means it  is not
compiled like normal  programs but is  instead read in as a  script and each
line is executed as it is reached - in a similar way to an @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}  script.
@{b}AREXX@{ub} can be used to provide a 'back-door' into many programs, allowing  you
to easily give  the program  instructions for  an operation  -  for instance
loading a drawer of GIF pictures  into an image processing  program, telling
it to  convert them to  greyscale and  to make them half the size,  and then
saving  them as JPEGs.   It can also be used to  create standalone programs, 
such as getting the user to input the year and then calculating and printing
out a simple calendar.

@{b}AREXX@{ub} comes with the Workbench distribution.
@Endnode

@Node "CLI" "The Command Line Interface"
@Next "LhA"
@Prev "Arexx"

@{bd "CLI"}

The  @{b}C@{ub}ommand  @{b}L@{ub}ine  @{b}I@{ub}nterface allows the user to communicate to the computer
via the keyboard. The @{b}Shell@{ub} is the Amiga's @{b}CLI@{ub}.
@Endnode

@Node "LhA" "LhA & LHZ"
@Next "LZX"
@Prev "CLI"

@{h "LhA"}  is  a  utility which allows you to @{b}compress@{ub} and @{"archive" link Arc} files. It was a
very  popular program for backup and distribution purposes (i.e. the @{b}AmiNET@{ub})
but  is now being surpassed in terms of @{b}decompression times@{ub} and @{b}archive size@{ub}
by @{"LZX" link LZX}.

@{b}LhA@{ub} archives can be compressed further.  If you archive all your files  into
an  LhA  archive  with  no  compression, then  archive  this  with @{b}LhA@{ub}  with
compression,  you can often save  quite a lot  more space, although you will
have to de-archive it twice.  I have not included  this facility in @{bl "LhA2LZX"},
because the same does not work with @{b}LZX@{ub},and it would have no real indication
how many times the archive had been re-archived, and may get too  complex to
be useful.  But it's nice to know anyway :^)

@{h "LHZ"} is similar to @{b}LhA@{ub}  and files @{b}archived@{ub} with  this are @{b}de-archived@{ub} by both
@{b}LhA@{ub} and @{b}LZX@{ub}.
@Endnode

@Node "LZX" "LZX"
@Next "ReqC"
@Prev "LhA"

@{h "LZX"} is a utility which allows you to @{b}compress@{ub} and @{"archive" link Arc} files with often a
great degree of @{b}compression@{ub}. It also @{b}decompresses@{ub} data faster than any other
popular  Amiga  program.  It  gives  greater @{b}compression@{ub} because it uses the
knowledge of previous files in the archive,using an ability to transparently
look  for similar @{b}compressible data@{ub} across @{b}multiple files@{ub} before adding them
to an archive.

See also @{" LhA/LZH " link LhA}
@Endnode

@Node "ReqC" "RequestChoice"
@Next "ReqF"
@Prev "LZX"

@{h "RequestChoice"}  brings up a requester in which the user is prompted to make a
choice.The @{b}title-, body- and button-texts@{ub} are configurable so that it may be
used in any  situation.  The value of the button pressed by the user is then
returned so that the relevant process is started.

See also @{" RequestFile " link ReqF}
@Endnode

@Node "ReqF" "RequestFile"
@Next "Index"
@Prev "ReqC"

@{h "RequestFile"}  brings up a  filerequester  in  which the  user is  prompted to
choose a file.The @{b}title-@{ub} and @{b}button-texts@{ub} are configurable so that it may be
used in any  situation. The chosen file name is then returned so that it may
be used later.

See also @{" RequestChoice " link ReqC}
@Endnode

